<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/12547103-reed-williams"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1520951242i/12547103._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/12547103-reed-williams">Reed Williams</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Nope. <br /><br />It's, I mean, not *justified*, but maybe understandable, kind of? But it's also just shockingly excessive and jarringly out of place. (Which I t<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Nope. <br /><br />It's, I mean, not *justified*, but maybe understandable, kind of? But it's also just shockingly excessive and jarringly out of place. (Which I think is very intentional on behalf of the author.) <br /><br />Like, in the context of a Jesse Bullington or Clive Barker novel, at least by that point in the story you've been desensitized to some degree by all of the many horrible things that have happened. In this one it's all pretty dry and, as far as violence goes, unchallenging right up until the point you're talking about.<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
